sample: Perform a single point calculation with the def2-SVP basis set, which is a Valence double-zeta basis set with “new” polarization functions. Include correlation fitting for the def2-SVP orbital basis and Weigend’s “universal” Coulomb fitting basis suitable for all def2 type basis sets. Avoid using with ECPs beyond Kr. Use the RI-wB2PLYP density functional, optimized for excitation energies. Utilize the RI approximation. Set the efficient RIJCOSX algorithm and stringent SCF convergence criteria. Turn on Kollmar's DIIS for SCF convergence acceleration, but keep SOSCF off. Set the storage format for numbers to single precision. Employ a heavier, higher-quality grid for Numerical Integration, close to the limit of an enormous grid. #p(hashtag)p.

! ri-wb2plyp sp def2-svp def2-svp/c rijcosx def2/j tightscf miniprint nomoprint nofinalgrid kdiis nososcf float defgrid3

%maxcore 8600
%scf

maxiter 512
directresetfreq 10
diismaxeq 10
end
%cpcm

refrac 1.8
end
%cis
nroots 4
triplets true
dcorr 1
maxcore 8600
end

Turn off the final grid in COSX, set the number of SCF iterations to 0 (working with provided starting orbitals), read MOs from a previous calculation, and use a heavier, higher-quality grid or Numerical Integration for better accuracy. Adjust output settings to print basis information (2) and molecular orbitals (1).

#b(hashtag)[ph]
Basis sets: @def2-tzvp=Valence triple-zeta basis set with “new” polarization functions. Note that this is quite similar to the older (“def”) TZVPP for the main group elements and TZVP for hydrogen.@autoaux=Automatic construction of a general purpose auxiliary basis for simultaneously fitting Coulomb, exchange and correlation calculations.@
Density functionals: @b3lyp=The popular B3LYP functional (20% HF exchange) as defined in the TurboMole program system@d3bj=Atom-pairwise dispersion correction to the DFT energy with Becke-Johnson damping@
Other: @uks=Selects spin unrestricted SCF@tightscf=Selects tight SCF convergence criteria (very stringent)@slowconv=Selects appropriate SCF convergence criteria for difficult cases (e.g., transition metal complexes)@uno=Produce UHF natural orbitals@uco=Calculate and plot the unrestricted corresponding orbitals@moread=Reads MOs from a previous calculation@notrah=Turns TRAH off@noiter=Sets the number of SCF iterations to 0. This works together with MOREAD and means that the program will work with the provided starting orbitals@
label:
! uks b3lyp def2-tzvp tightscf slowconv uno uco d3bj autoaux moread notrah noiter 
%moinp "3-1_b3lyp_fat_pathologic.qro"
%pal nprocs 32
end
%maxcore 7500
%basis
newgto fe "cp(ppp)" end
end
%method
specialgridatoms 26
specialgridintacc 7
end
%output
printlevel normal
print[ p_basis       ] 2
print[ p_mos         ] 1
print[ p_density     ] 1
print[ p_spindensity ] 1
end
#b(hashtag)[ph]

Density functionals: @pbe=Selects the Perdew-Burke-Erzerhof GGA functional@d3bj=Atom-pairwise dispersion correction to the DFT energy with Becke-Johnson damping@
Other: @normalopt=Selects default optimization convergence (uses tolerances for root-mean-square displacement and maximum displacement)@miniprint=Selects the minimal output@nomoprint=Dont print any of the MOs@defgrid3=heavier, higher-quality grid or Numerical Integration, that is close to the limit if one considers an enormous grid as a reference.@
label:
! zoom-neb-ts pbe d3bj def2-svp def2/j normalopt nofinalgrid miniprint nomoprint defgrid3
%pal nprocs 40 end
%maxcore 4300
%neb
neb_end_xyzfile "end.xyz"
end
#b(hashtag)ccl

sample: Perform a spin-restricted SCF calculation with tight convergence criteria (very stringent). Ensure the output is set to normal and produce UHF natural orbitals. Use the RIJCOSX algorithm for efficient treatment of Coulomb and Exchange terms, with a polarized atoms guess.
label:
! rohf tightscf normalprint uno rijcosx patom
%pal nprocs 8
end
%basis
basis "def2-tzvpp"
aux "def2/j"
auxjk "def2/jk"
auxc "def2-tzvpp/c"
end
%maxcore 5000
%scf 
maxdisk 40000
end      
%casscf
nel 4
norb 5
mult 5,3,1
nroots 5,45,50
shiftup 0.5
shiftdn 0.5
switchconv 0.003
orbstep superci
switchstep diis
actorbs dorbs
printwf true
trafostep ri
nevpt2 true 
rel
printlevel 3
dosoc true
domagnetization true dosusceptibility true lebedevprec 5
npointsfstep 5
magfieldstep 100.0
magtemperaturemin 2.0
magtemperaturemax 2.0
magtemperaturenpoints 1
magfieldmin 0.0
magfieldmax 70000.0
magnpoints 20
sustempmin 1.0
sustempmax 300.0
susnpoints 300
susstatfieldmin 0.0
susstatfieldmax 0.0
susstatfieldnpoints 1
gtensor true
nreducedstates 1  
end
maxiter 550
end
%output 
print[ p_basis ] 2
print[ p_mos ] 1
end
#s=[sh]

sample:
#c1(hashtag)so1
Basis sets: @def2-tzvpp=TZVPP basis set with “new” polarization functions.@def2/j=Weigend’s “universal” Coulomb fitting basis that is suitable for all def2 type basis sets. Assumes the use of ECPs beyond Kr (do not use with DKH/ZORA).@
Density functionals: @wb97x-d3bj=Modified version of wB97X-V with D3BJ dispersion correction by Najibi and Goerigk@
Other: @opt=Selects a geometry optimization calculation (using internal redundant coordinates)@rijcosx=Sets the flag for the efficient RIJCOSXalgorithm (treat the Coulomb term via RI and the Exchange term via seminumerical integration).@verytightscf=Selects very tight SCF convergence criteria (extremely stringent)@defgrid3=heavier, higher-quality grid or Numerical Integration, that is close to the limit if one considers an enormous grid as a reference.@verytightopt=Selects very tight optimization convergence (specifies tolerances for energy and root-mean-square gradient)@
label:
! wb97x-d3bj opt freq def2-tzvpp def2/j rijcosx verytightscf
! pal8 defgrid3 verytightopt
%maxcore 4096
%geom				    maxiter 300
    calc_hess true
end
%chelpg			  grid 0.1
  rmax 3.0
end
%method
  z_tol    1e-10
end
%elprop
  dipole true
  quadrupole true
  polar 1
end

sample: Perform a calculation with the def2-svp basis set, using the `C1=CC=CC=C1` molecule. Utilize default optimization convergence, tight SCF convergence criteria, minimal output, do not print MOs, and set storage format for numbers to single precision. ! normalopt def2-svp rijcosx def2/j def2-svp/c tightscf miniprint nomoprint defgrid1 kdiis nososcf float
%pal nprocs 6 end

method dft
functional hyb_gga_xc_wb97x_v
end

maxiter 512
directresetfreq 10
diismaxeq 10
end
%cis
mode aoints
nroots 4
iroot 1
irootmult singlet
triplets false
maxcore 2000
end

sample: Perform a single point calculation using the popular B3LYP functional with 20% HF exchange, as defined in the TurboMole program system. The calculation will be carried out with the Pople 6-31G basis set and its modifications (H–Zn) with one set of first polarization functions on all atoms except H. The efficient RIJCOSX algorithm will be utilized for treating the Coulomb and Exchange terms efficiently. Additionally, tight SCF convergence criteria will be applied for stringent convergence, with minimal output and MO printing disabled. Kollmar's DIIS will be used for SCF convergence acceleration, while SOSCF will be turned off. Use a heavier, higher-quality grid for Numerical Integration, close to the limit of an enormous grid as a reference. Consider the molecule represented by '#c1=nn=1'.
label:
! b3lyp 6-31g* sp rijcosx autoaux tightscf miniprint nomoprint nofinalgrid kdiis nososcf defgrid3
%pal nprocs 40 end
%maxcore 4300
%scf
scfmode direct
guessmode fmatrix
maxiter 512
directresetfreq 10
diismaxeq 10
end
%cis
nroots 10
triplets true
maxcore 4300
end

sample: Perform a calculation using the ZORA adapted valence double-zeta basis set with "new" polarization functions (zora-def2-svp), including correlation fitting for the def2-SVP orbital basis (def2-svp/c). Select the scalar relativistic ZORA Hamiltonian (zora) and invoke the SOMF(1X) treatment of the spin-orbit coupling operator (somf(1x)). Allow for a RHF calculation even if the system is open-shell and utilize MOs from a previous calculation. Set the number of SCF iterations to 0 to work with the provided starting orbitals.
label:
! allowrhf zora-def2-svp def2-svp/c zora
! somf(1x) moread noiter
%moinp "mnf6_casscf.gbw"
%mrci
  citype mrci
  intmode ritrafo
  soc
    dossc true
    dosoc true
   end
  newblock 5 *
    nroots 5
    excitations none
    refs cas (4,5) end
   end
  newblock 3 *
    nroots 45
    excitations none
    refs cas (4,5) end
   end
 end

sample: Perform a quantum chemical calculation using the ZORA adapted valence double-zeta basis set with “new” polarization functions (zora-def2-svp) and the general-purpose Coulomb fitting basis set (sarc/j) for the molecule. Utilize the popular B3LYP functional (20% HF exchange) for the density functional. Include the settings for spin-unrestricted SCF, the scalar relativistic ZORA Hamiltonian, the efficient RIJCOSXalgorithm, the conductor-like polarizable continuum model (CPCM) with a water solvent, and the SOMF(1X) treatment of the spin-orbit coupling operator.
label:
! uks b3lyp zora-def2-svp sarc/j zora rijcosx
! cpcm(water) somf(1x)
%paras
  r_ml  = 1.887   dist  = 0.05   end
*int -3 5
mn     0   0   0   0.000           0.000     0.000
f      1   0   0   {r_ml}          0.000     0.000
f      1   2   0   {r_ml}        180.000     0.000
f      1   2   3   {r_ml}         90.000     0.000
f      1   2   4   {r_ml}         90.000   180.000
f      1   2   5   {r_ml+dist}    90.000    90.000
f      1   2   5   {r_ml+dist}    90.000   270.000
*
%eprnmr
  dtensor ssandso
  dss = uno
  dsoc = cp
 end

Additionally, the efficient RIJCOSX algorithm will be utilized. Control settings for the CPCM include using the vdW Gaussian surface type, while the output will include the Hirschfeld population analysis tagged as p_hirshfeld. The calculation will use 3000 MB of scratch memory and will run on 16 processors.
label:
! freq pbeh-3c rijcosx cpcm(acetonitrile)
%cpcm
surfacetype vdw_gaussian
end
%output 
xyzfile=true 
end 
%scf 
maxiter 250 
end
%output
print[p_hirshfeld] = 1
end
% maxcore
3000
%pal nprocs 16
end
#p(hashtag)scl

sample: ** Perform a quantum mechanical calculation with the def2-TZVP basis set, using the B3LYP density functional for the [bh]f molecule. Additionally, include the def2/J basis for Coulomb fitting, the D3BJ dispersion correction, and utilize spin unrestricted SCF. Set very tight SCF convergence criteria and use the RIJCOSX algorithm for efficient calculations. Make sure to read MOs from a previous calculation, turn off the final grid in COSX, and start with provided starting orbitals with zero SCF iterations. Consider using the heavier, higher-quality grid specified in DEFGRID3 for accurate results.
label:
!uks b3lyp def2-tzvp def2/j d3bj verytightscf rijcosx nofinalgrid nofinalgridx noautostart moread noiter  defgrid3
%pal nprocs 24
end
%moinp "p_is_opt_gbw.qro"
%basis
newgto fe "cp(ppp)" end
newauxgto fe "def2/j" end
end
%output 
print[ p_basis ] 2 
print[ p_mos ] 1 
end
#[bh]f

sample: Perform a calculation using the PBE hybrid density functional with a small AO basis set (ps1), treating the Coulomb term via RI and the Exchange term via seminumerical integration. sample: Perform a single point calculation with spin unrestricted SCF using the def2-SVP basis set with "new" polarization functions. Utilize the def2-SVP/c correlation fitting and Weigend’s "universal" Coulomb fitting basis (def2/j). Enable efficient RIJCOSX algorithm for Coulomb term treatment and seminumerical integration for Exchange term. Select strong SCF convergence criteria, minimal output, and print basis set in input format. Additionally, print MO coefficients and set first default grid points for numerical integration. Turn on Kollmar's DIIS for SCF convergence acceleration, disable SOSCF, and set storage format for numbers to single precision. Consider the molecule represented by the SMILES notation #b(hashtag)[ph].
label:
! uks ri-scs-wpbepp86 sp def2-svp def2-svp/c rijcosx def2/j strongscf miniprint printbasis printmos defgrid1 kdiis nososcf float

%maxcore 2000
%scf

maxiter 512
directresetfreq 10
diismaxeq 10
end
%mp2
density relaxed
end
%cis
donto true
mode riints_disk
nroots 32
dcorr 1
maxcore 2000
end

sample: Perform a quantum calculation using the def2-tzvpp basis set with the new polarization functions, and the def2/j basis set for Coulomb fitting (excluding use with ECPs beyond Kr). Symmetry will be enforced, and molecular orbitals will be read from a previous calculation with no SCF iterations. UHF natural orbitals and unrestricted corresponding orbitals will be calculated and plotted. The program will use a heavier, higher-quality grid for numerical integration. The molecule of interest is Phenanthrene (C14H10).

end

end
